Well, you have to consider the Westermarck effect whenever visualizing hypothetical incest.
I.e. there's a powerful sexual aversion that's instilled in humans over the course of either growing up with, or raising, others.
This isn't biological (meaning it happens with "siblings" not biologically related too, as long as they spend enough time together growing up), but psychological.

Basically, what this means, is that for a whole damn lot of people, incest is a -very- alluring and appealing fetish, but only as long as it's about someone else, or about hypothetical siblings/relatives.
In both these cases you're free from the Westermarck effect, since it's either incest between someone else (with you projecting/fantasizing, like with a fapfic), or incest between yourself and other people (people with whom you haven't actually grown up, like with a masturbation fantasy).

To examplify; try imagining yourself as a biological relative with someone you find sexually attractive. It's arousing.
Now try imagining yourself having sexual relations with your own ACTUAL mother or sister. Not as alluring (for the vast majority).

To answer your question , then, it's far too easy for me to say YES ALL OF MY YES
..but I wouldn't really know how I'd actually feel, had I actually raised them as my daughters.

>>9324623
Because it immediately looks cringey, by merit of instantly calling to mind the fact that it---probably more than other works---specifically is supposed to depict someone having facial hair in real life. Most often the artist/commissioner.

Although granted, it's not as cringey as anthros/fursonas with goatees and shit, it's still awkward.

tl;dr: the less uniquely defining visual characteristics in the human character depicted, the less awkward it is for others to enjoy the art. (Since the character is more generic, it doesn't "grab" the attention as much, and it doesn't make the drawing personal, enabling others to enjoy it more easily.)
